				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Playing songs while fighting question...<a name="9322"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 20 03 5:46 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>This is probably a question that was answered among you folks a while ago, but I had no luck using the &quot;search&quot; function so I wanted to ask.
<br />

<br />
The question is dpoes having auto-attack &quot;on&quot; increase the chance of missed notes, even if your target is too far away to hit?
<br />

<br />
Here is the situation that led me to ask the question:  Playing earlier today in DL, I was meleeing/twisting while a Monk pulled critters to the group.  I would play amp and mana song in between fights until the Monk called &quot;Incoming %T&quot;, at which time I would /assist Monk (triggering auto-attack) and wait for mob to get within range of Snare/slow song.  When it was in range, I'd hit snare/slow song.  It seemed to me, and I have no benchmark for actual comparison, I was missing more notes when auto-attack was on and I was essentially spamming myself with &quot;your target is too far away&quot; messages.  When I adjusted my style and kept auto-attack off until I had landed snare/slow, it seemed there were less missed notes.
<br />

<br />
Sorry for not being able to provide a solid numerical equation of, say, 100 attempts with attack on and 100 without to start with.  I just didn't have the chance yet, though I plan to keep a notebook with me to tick off the difference.  
<br />

<br />
I have a feeling I'm smoking crack and this is just a pipe-dream, but if it does make a difference, I figured it would be good to know.  Any experience with this would be appreciated, and I'll post any results I come up with later on this same thread.
<br />

<br />
Thanks- 
<br />

<br />
Mance</span></td>
