				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Playing songs while fighting question...<a name="9462"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 23 03 3:09 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Liars, d*mn liars and statisticians (and Sony).
<br />

<br />
I understand and am happy that some folks have done a lot of work to attempt to see the effects of dext and charis on missed notes.
<br />

<br />
To get real statistical results, you would have to do a lot of it, you would have to do it with multiple lvl songs at each bard level.
<br />

<br />
You would have to do it in the exact same circumstance with no code changes during the testing (patches). Then you would have to assume a subsequent patch did not change it.
<br />

<br />
If you have a very good sampling under well controlled conditionsm made no miniscule but critical errors in your assumptions, and got results that had a 70% assurance that they were within 20% of accurate, you would have a good sample.
<br />

<br />
What value would that be if you were interested in a 10% variance?
<br />

<br />
I respect those folks work, and I think they have given good evidence there is not a big difference....but disproven any effect? 
<br />

<br />
Not for my money.
<br />

<br />
Compare that to some guy in charge of writing the new code for the character creation screen walking over to another department in charge of bard coding and asking them... what stats are useful for a bard...and getting an answer, &quot;well, we factor in charisma and dexterity in determining missed notes...&quot;
<br />

<br />
Would a Sony (or whatever company is actually doing the coding) employee be either willfully or unwittingly wrong about that?
<br />

<br />
Well...</span></td>
